ANTHRAX, HUMAN, BOVINE - BANGLADESH (15)
****************************************
A ProMED-mail post
<http://www.promedmail.org>
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
<http://www.isid.org>

[1]
Date: Tue 14 Sep 2010
Source: The New Nation (Bangladesh) [edited]
<http://nation.ittefaq.com/issues/2010/09/14/news0016.htm>


Another 16 anthrax infected people were detected yesterday [13 Sep
2010] in 2 districts of the country. The newly infected people raised
the infected accounts to 495.

Among the newly contaminated people, 7 were from the Araihazar
Upazila [sub district] of Narayangonj district while the 9 others
were from Charghat Upazila of Rajshahi district. The detected people
of Araihazar area was sent to Upazila Health Centre yesterday [13 Sep
2010] and the on-duty doctor identified them as anthrax infected.
Medical officer on duty Dr Zinat Ara said they are certainly infected
by anthrax but no need to be anxious as we have taken necessary
initiatives for their proper treatment.

Referring to the infection, locals said a resident of Kalyanadi
village bought a cow just before the Eid and doubted that it might be
anthrax affected. Later, he brought the cow to the local livestock
hospital for its treatment. Finding no improvement of treatment, he
slaughtered the cow and distributed its meat to at least 50 families
of that area. As a result, some of them got infected by eating its
meat.

Mentioning the latest [numbers of human anthrax caes], director of
Institute of Epidemiology Disease Control and Research (IEDCR) said
"we have detected 495 cases from 18 Aug 2010 to 13 Sep 2010 and after
treatment more than 90 percent of the infected people have recovered
while others are under treatment." He also said that close monitoring
and a massive awareness programme was going on.

The IEDCR director suggested that people should not pay heed to
rumours that fish, birds, etc are being infected by anthrax. It only
infects cattle and never spreads from human to human.

Meanwhile, the local residents of Dhamrai had been given anthrax
vaccine yesterday [13 Sep 2010], though the deaths of birds and
animals in that area were not caused by anthrax. Dhamrai health and
family planning officer Sukumar Sarker said the locals were given
anthrax vaccine as a precaution, though no anthrax affected people
were identified or admitted to hospitals.

--
