******
[2]
Date: Sat 11 Sep 2010
Source: bdnews24.com [edited]
<http://www.bdnews24.com/details.php?id=173118&cid=2>


The officials have collected specimens from the cow and other
animals, also asked people not to consume meat of that cow, which
they suspect might have contracted anthrax.

Local residents said 41 families of Kayetpara together bought 3 cows
from Kalampur market. Those cows were brought from Sirajganj, from
where anthrax has spread recently. One of the buyers said one of the
cows had lesions on its body. "It was slaughtered on Friday night [10
Sep 2010] and the families took their share of meat. But as it was
late, the blood was not covered up with mud," he added.

The locals informed the Upazila livestock officials that for some
inexplicable reasons, several ducks, chickens, pigeons, crows, dogs,
and cats were found dead in the area until Saturday noon [11 Sep
2010].

Experts from Dhaka also visited the area, collected specimens from
the dead and the cow's blood, and sent them to the Dhaka's Institute
of Epidemiology Disease Control and Research (IEDCR). Deputy director
of the divisional livestock directorate Dr Mosaddek Hossain said:
"The matter can be resolved after we get the report in 3 days." But,
primarily, the reason could be 'blood poisoning', he said. "We're
taking steps to vaccinate the people who consumed meat of that ailing
cow. A monitoring team will also be sent to the area," he added. The
official, however, claimed that no bird or animal dies of anthrax.

None of those who had the beef was admitted to hospital and there had
been no anthrax patients identified in Dhamrai.

Until 9 Sep 2010, at least 479 people have contracted anthrax in 8
Upazila around the country since 18 Aug 2010.

